<h1>STFL - Structured Terminal Forms Language/Library</h1>

<p>
STFL is a library which implements a <b>curses-based widget set</b> for text
terminals. The STFL API can be used from <b>C, SPL, Python, Perl and Ruby</b>.
Since the API is only 14 simple function calls big and there are already
generic SWIG bindings it is very easy to port STFL to additional scripting
languages.
</p>

<p>
A special language (the Structured Terminal Forms Language) is used to
describe STFL GUIs. The language is designed to be easy and fast to write
so an application programmer does not need to spend ages fiddling around
with the GUI and can concentrate on the more interesting programming tasks.
</p>

<p>
The STFL documentation can be found <a href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/README"
>here</a>.
</p>

<h3>Example Scripts</h3>

<p>
<b>SPL API:</b> &nbsp;
A little database frontend for an address database (I've used the data from the
linux kernel CREDITS file as expample data). The sourcecode of the script can
be downloaded from <a href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/spl/example.spl"
>here</a>. The script is written in <a href="../spl/">SPL</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a href="screenshot01.png" target="_blank"><img src="screenshot01_thumb.png"></a>
<a href="screenshot02.png" target="_blank"><img src="screenshot02_thumb.png"></a>
</p>

<p>
<b>C API:</b> &nbsp;
A simple test for different STFL layouting algorithms. It is written in C and
using an external STFL file. The C code can be found <a
href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/example.c">here</a> and the STFL code
can be found <a href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/example.stfl">here</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a href="screenshot03.png" target="_blank"><img src="screenshot03_thumb.png"></a>
</p>

<p>
<b>Perl API:</b> &nbsp;
Another STFL example program (a little mp3/ogg jukebox application), this time
written in Perl. The program code can be found <a
href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/perl5/example.pl">here</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a href="screenshot04.png" target="_blank"><img src="screenshot04_thumb.png"></a>
</p>

<p>
<b>Ruby API:</b> &nbsp;
A little vCard generator written by Andreas Krennmair. The program code can be
found <a href="http://svn.clifford.at/stfl/trunk/ruby/example.rb">here</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a href="screenshot05.png" target="_blank"><img src="screenshot05_thumb.png"></a>
</p>

